        "@odata.context": "https://azs-net-azsearchsdktest.search.windows.net/$metadata#Microsoft.WindowsAzure.Search.Core.Models.V2026_05_01_Preview.Agents.AgentRetrievalResponse",
        "response": [
          {
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "I don't have access to up-to-date external lists right now, so I can't pull or cite current rankings. However, I can summarize commonly recognized top luxury hotels and what makes a hotel \"best\" so you can evaluate options. If you want, I can later fetch current ranked lists when I can access sources.\n\nWhat defines the \"best\" luxury hotels (key features to look for)\n- Exceptional service: highly trained staff, strong guest-to-staff ratio, personalized service and concierge support.\n- Outstanding rooms and suites: spacious layouts, high-quality bedding and finishes, thoughtful amenities, sometimes private pools or butler service.\n- Fine dining and beverage options: on-site Michelin-starred or critically acclaimed restaurants and specialty bars.\n- Facilities and wellness: full-service spas, fitness centers, pools (indoor/outdoor/infinity), wellness programming.\n- Location and exclusivity: prime city center, iconic beachfront, remote private-island or historic estate settings.\n- Design and history: notable architecture, celebrated designers, historic preservation, unique local character.\n- Privacy, security, and discretion: for high-profile guests, with private entrances, villas, or dedicated staff.\n- Consistent, documented excellence: awards, star ratings, and traveler reviews across platforms.\n\nExamples of types and names (widely regarded in luxury travel discussions)\n- Iconic city palaces and grande dame hotels: often found in major capitals and known for history and opulence (examples commonly cited in travel writing: historic hotels in Paris, Vienna, London).\n- Ultra-luxury urban skyscraper hotels: offering skyline views, Michelin restaurants, and top-tier service (often in New York, Hong Kong, Dubai).\n- Private-island and resort properties: secluded villas, overwater bungalows, butler service, and high-end marine activities (frequently in the Maldives, Seychelles, South Pacific).\n- Safari lodges and remote retreats: luxury tents/lodges with guided safaris, all-inclusive service, and prime wildlife viewing (commonly in East and Southern Africa).\n- Mountain and ski luxury hotels: chalet-style service, ski-in/ski-out access, heated pools and spas (Alps, Rockies).\n\nHow to find the current “best” lists\n- Annual industry awards and guides: look for recent reports from sources such as Condé Nast Traveler, Forbes Travel Guide, Travel + Leisure, and Michelin (they publish hotel awards or gold lists).\n- Professional inspector ratings: Forbes Travel Guide stars and AAA/CAA diamonds where available.\n- Aggregated traveler ratings: top-rated properties on major travel platforms (with attention to sample size and recency).\n- Specialist luxury travel advisers and concierge services: many curate up-to-date, vetted recommendations and can book exclusive experiences.\n\nIf you want a tailored recommendation, tell me:\n- Destination or region (city, country, or “beach / mountain / safari / urban”)\n- Travel dates or season\n- Travel party (couple, family, solo, group)\n- Priorities (romance, privacy, dining, spa, activities, proximity to sights)\n- Budget range per night (approximate)\n\nWith that I can give targeted hotel suggestions and advice for choosing or booking. If you'd like, I can also fetch the latest ranked lists and specific property names now — tell me which sources you prefer (for example, Condé Nast Traveler, Forbes Travel Guide, Travel + Leisure) and I will retrieve them."
              }
            ]
          }
